h1. Landscape FQDN Change Runbook: caal.dev → calix.local

*Host:* {{pln-landscape01}}
*Old FQDN:* {{pln-landscape01.caal.dev}}
*New FQDN:* {{pln-landscape01.calix.local}}
*Service impact:* Landscape clients cannot check in or register during the cutover. Schedule a maintenance window.

-----

h2. 0. Pre-flight (do this before the maintenance window)

h3. 0.1 DNS

Confirm the following records exist in {{calix.local}} and resolve from both the Landscape server and a sample client:

- {{pln-landscape01.calix.local}} A → server IP
- Reverse PTR for the server IP → {{pln-landscape01.calix.local}}
- Any vanity alias clients will use (e.g. {{pln-landscape.calix.local}} CNAME → {{pln-landscape01.calix.local}})

{code:bash}
dig +short pln-landscape01.calix.local
dig +short -x <server_ip>
{code}

h3. 0.2 Inventory of registered clients

You’ll need to re-point every registered client after the cutover. From the Landscape UI or DB, export the current client list. Plan how the new {{/etc/landscape/client.conf}} will be pushed (Ansible, Landscape script, manual).

h3. 0.3 Corporate CA trust

The new cert will be issued by {{corp_pki.calix.local}}, not the existing self-signed CA. Every client will need the corporate CA chain in its trust store *before* it can talk to the new URL. Confirm {{/etc/ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt}} (or equivalent) on a sample client already trusts the corporate root, or plan to deploy it.

h3. 0.4 Backups

{code:bash}
sudo cp -a /etc/postfix /etc/postfix.bak.$(date +%F)
sudo cp -a /etc/apache2/sites-available /etc/apache2/sites-available.bak.$(date +%F)
sudo cp -a /etc/landscape /etc/landscape.bak.$(date +%F)
sudo cp -a /etc/ssl /etc/ssl.bak.$(date +%F)
sudo cp /etc/hostname /etc/hostname.bak
sudo cp /etc/hosts /etc/hosts.bak
{code}

-----

h2. 1. Hostname

{code:bash}
sudo hostnamectl set-hostname pln-landscape01.calix.local
{code}

Update {{/etc/hosts}} so {{hostname -f}} returns the new FQDN. The line that previously referenced the old name must be replaced — typically the {{127.0.1.1}} line on Ubuntu, or the line bound to the server’s real IP:

{code}
<server_ip>   pln-landscape01.calix.local pln-landscape01
{code}

Verify:

{code:bash}
hostname
hostname -f         # must return pln-landscape01.calix.local
hostname -d         # must return calix.local
{code}

{panel:bgColor=#fffae6}
If {{hostname -f}} returns anything else, *stop and fix /etc/hosts before continuing* — Landscape and Apache both rely on this.
{panel}

-----

h2. 2. Postfix

Edit {{/etc/postfix/main.cf}} and update any entries referencing the old FQDN. At minimum, check:

- {{myhostname}} → {{pln-landscape01.calix.local}}
- {{mydomain}} → {{calix.local}}
- {{myorigin}} (if hardcoded)
- {{mydestination}} (if it lists FQDNs)

Validate and reload:

{code:bash}
sudo postfix check
sudo systemctl reload postfix
{code}

{panel:bgColor=#ffebe6}
*Do not run {{postmap main.cf}}.* {{postmap}} is for indexed lookup tables ({{canonical}}, {{transport}}, {{virtual}}, etc.), not {{main.cf}}. Running it on {{main.cf}} produces a junk {{.db}} file Postfix ignores.
{panel}

Verify:

{code:bash}
postconf myhostname mydomain myorigin
echo “test” | mail -s “FQDN change test” root
sudo tail -f /var/log/mail.log
{code}

-----

h2. 3. Apache vhost

h3. 3.1 Disable old site, rename config

{code:bash}
sudo a2dissite pln-landscape01.caal.dev
cd /etc/apache2/sites-available
sudo mv pln-landscape01.caal.dev.conf pln-landscape01.calix.local.conf
{code}

If there’s also an SSL variant (e.g. {{*-ssl.conf}}), rename that too.

h3. 3.2 Edit the vhost

Open {{/etc/apache2/sites-available/pln-landscape01.calix.local.conf}} and replace *every* occurrence of the old FQDN with the new one. There will be more than just {{ServerName}} — Landscape’s vhost contains {{RewriteRule}} lines that embed the hostname in proxied URLs, e.g.:

{code}
RewriteRule ^/message-system http://localhost:8090/++vh++https:pln-landscape01.calix.local:443/++/ [P,L]
RewriteRule ^/(.*)           http://localhost:8080/++vh++https:pln-landscape01.calix.local:443/++/$1 [P]
{code}

Quick check for any stragglers:

{code:bash}
sudo grep -rn ‘caal.dev|pln-landscape01.caal’ /etc/apache2/
{code}

In each {{<VirtualHost>}} block, set:

{code}
ServerName pln-landscape01.calix.local
ServerAdmin webmaster@calix.local
{code}

(Set these once per vhost block, not three times.)

h3. 3.3 Enable new site

{code:bash}
sudo a2ensite pln-landscape01.calix.local
sudo apache2ctl configtest
{code}

Do *not* reload Apache yet — wait until the new TLS cert is in place (Section 4), otherwise Apache will fail to start because {{SSLCertificateFile}} points at a path that doesn’t exist or doesn’t match the new ServerName.

-----

h2. 4. TLS certificate

h3. 4.1 CSR config

Create {{landscape_server.conf}}:

{code}
[ req ]
default_md         = sha256
prompt             = no
req_extensions     = req_ext
distinguished_name = req_distinguished_name

[ req_distinguished_name ]
commonName             = pln-landscape01.calix.local
countryName            = US
stateOrProvinceName    = California
localityName           = San Jose
organizationName       = Calix
organizationalUnitName = Engineering Operations

[ req_ext ]
subjectAltName = @alt_names

[ alt_names ]
DNS.1 = pln-landscape01.calix.local
DNS.2 = pln-landscape01
DNS.3 = pln-landscape.calix.local        # only if vanity alias is used
{code}

Notes on what changed from the original:

- {{commonName}} was {{vault.calix.local}} (leftover from a Vault template) — now the actual Landscape FQDN.
- SAN entries start at {{DNS.1}}, not {{DNS.0}} (OpenSSL convention).
- The new FQDN is in SAN — modern clients ignore CN and require SAN match (RFC 6125).

h3. 4.2 Generate CSR and key

{code:bash}
openssl req -new -newkey rsa:2048 -nodes   
-keyout landscape_server.key   
-out   landscape_server.csr   
-config landscape_server.conf

openssl req -text -noout -verify -in landscape_server.csr
{code}

Confirm the output shows the correct CN and *all* SANs.

h3. 4.3 Submit and download

Submit the CSR contents at {{https://corp_pki.calix.local/certsrv/certrqxt.asp}}, request a 2-year cert, download the issued cert as {{.p7b}}.

Convert the {{.p7b}} (which contains the leaf + intermediates + root concatenated):

{code:bash}
openssl pkcs7 -print_certs -in certnew.p7b -out certnew_chain.pem
{code}

Open {{certnew_chain.pem}} in an editor — you’ll see multiple {{—–BEGIN CERTIFICATE—–}} blocks, each preceded by {{subject=}} and {{issuer=}} lines. Split them:

- The block where {{subject}} = {{pln-landscape01.calix.local}} → save as {{landscape_server.pem}} (leaf cert)
- The remaining blocks (issuing CA, then root) → save as {{landscape_server_ca.crt}} (chain bundle, leaf-issuer first)

If you’d rather script the split:

{code:bash}

# Quick visual confirmation of the order/contents

awk ‘/subject=|issuer=/’ certnew_chain.pem
{code}

h3. 4.4 Install

{code:bash}
sudo install -o root -g root              -m 0644 landscape_server.pem    /etc/ssl/certs/landscape_server.pem
sudo install -o root -g root              -m 0644 landscape_server_ca.crt /etc/ssl/certs/landscape_server_ca.crt
sudo install -o root -g ssl-cert          -m 0640 landscape_server.key    /etc/ssl/private/landscape_server.key
{code}

(On distros without {{ssl-cert}} group, use {{root:root 0600}} — but then {{www-data}} needs to be able to read the key, which usually means Apache must read it as root before privsep. The {{ssl-cert}} group is the cleaner path on Ubuntu.)

Confirm Apache’s SSL vhost references these exact paths ({{SSLCertificateFile}}, {{SSLCertificateKeyFile}}, {{SSLCertificateChainFile}} or {{SSLCACertificateFile}}).

-----

h2. 5. Landscape service config

This is the step missing from the original runbook. Hostname + Apache vhost is *not* enough.

Edit {{/etc/landscape/service.conf}} and update any FQDN references. The key one is:

{code}
[global]
root_url = https://pln-landscape01.calix.local/
{code}

Also check for {{message_url}} and {{ping_url}} overrides if present (normally derived from {{root_url}} and not set explicitly).

Search for stragglers across the Landscape config dir:

{code:bash}
sudo grep -rn ‘caal.dev|pln-landscape01.caal’ /etc/landscape/
{code}

-----

h2. 6. Restart in order

{code:bash}

# 1. Apache (now that cert is in place)

sudo apache2ctl configtest && sudo systemctl reload apache2

# 2. Landscape services

sudo lsctl restart

# 3. Confirm services are up

sudo lsctl status
sudo systemctl status apache2 postfix
{code}

-----

h2. 7. Verification

h3. 7.1 On the server

{code:bash}

# Cert is being served correctly

echo | openssl s_client -connect pln-landscape01.calix.local:443 -servername pln-landscape01.calix.local 2>/dev/null   
| openssl x509 -noout -subject -issuer -dates -ext subjectAltName

# Ping endpoint

curl -fv http://pln-landscape01.calix.local/ping

# Message-system endpoint (expects a 200/405-ish response, not connection refused)

curl -fv -k https://pln-landscape01.calix.local/message-system

# Landscape logs are clean

sudo tail -n 200 /var/log/landscape/*.log | grep -iE ‘error|trace|fail’ | head
{code}

h3. 7.2 On a test client

Pick one non-critical Landscape client first. Push the new corporate CA into its trust store if not already present, then re-run {{landscape-config}} with the new URL:

{code:bash}
sudo landscape-config   
–account-name standalone   
–url      https://pln-landscape01.calix.local/message-system   
–ping-url http://pln-landscape01.calix.local/ping   
–computer-title “$(hostname)”

sudo systemctl restart landscape-client
sudo tail -f /var/log/landscape/broker.log
{code}

Confirm the client appears in the Landscape UI and accepts a trivial action (e.g. info refresh) before rolling out to the rest of the fleet.

h3. 7.3 Fleet rollout

Push the updated {{/etc/landscape/client.conf}} (URL + {{ssl_public_key}} if applicable) to remaining clients via your usual config-management path. Don’t do this until the test client in 7.2 is confirmed healthy.

-----

h2. 8. Rollback plan

If Apache fails to start, clients can’t reach the server, or the cert won’t validate:

{code:bash}

# 1. Stop Apache

sudo systemctl stop apache2

# 2. Restore the old vhost

sudo a2dissite pln-landscape01.calix.local
sudo cp /etc/apache2/sites-available.bak.<DATE>/pln-landscape01.caal.dev.conf   
/etc/apache2/sites-available/
sudo a2ensite pln-landscape01.caal.dev

# 3. Restore Landscape config

sudo cp /etc/landscape.bak.<DATE>/service.conf /etc/landscape/service.conf

# 4. Restore hostname

sudo hostnamectl set-hostname pln-landscape01.caal.dev
sudo cp /etc/hosts.bak /etc/hosts

# 5. Restart

sudo systemctl restart apache2
sudo lsctl restart
{code}

The old TLS cert and key were not deleted, so the old vhost’s {{SSLCertificateFile}} paths should still be valid. Confirm before declaring rollback successful:

{code:bash}
echo | openssl s_client -connect pln-landscape01.caal.dev:443 -servername pln-landscape01.caal.dev 2>/dev/null   
| openssl x509 -noout -subject -dates
{code}

Clients should resume check-ins automatically.

-----

h2. 9. Cleanup (after fleet has migrated)

- Remove the old {{caal.dev}} DNS records.
- Delete the old self-signed CA from clients’ trust stores if no longer needed.
- Remove old Apache vhost config files and old key/cert files from {{/etc/ssl/}}.
- Update any monitoring (Zabbix, etc.) targeting the old FQDN.
- Update internal docs / wiki / runbook references.